{
  "doc_id": "39775",
  "text": "It appears that opiate mediation of eating is involved in the maintenance, rather than the initiation of eating [CITATION_1] , because morphine increased the speed of eating but not the latency to eat in food-deprived rats [CITATION_2] . Because U50,488 affected neither response, it was concluded that the u, not K, receptors were involved in the regulation of feeding in deprivation tests [CITATION_3] . The K receptors may be triggered by the taste of food, and may sustain feeding by facilitating incentive rewards [CITATION_4] or by delaying the development of satiation [CITATION_5] .",
